When you call IdealGasMix, you should specify two arguments:  the file 
name (which may be either a .cti or .xml file), and the id tag of the 
phase within the file that you want to use.  For example, file 
gri30.cti (or gri30.xml) contains three phase definitions: &quot;gri30&quot; 
implements GRI-3.0 with no transport properties, &quot;gri30_mix&quot; uses 
mixture-averaged transport properties, and &quot;gri30_multi&quot; uses 
multicomponent ones.  From Python, Cantera builds the first phase it 
finds in the file if the id tag is not specified, which in this case 
would be &quot;gri30&quot; with no transport properties.  Currently, the C++ code 
does not do this - you have to specify an id tag.

But it probably should behave like it does in Python, and it is an easy 
fix to get this behavior.  In file Cantera/src/importCTML.cpp, find 
function &#39;buildSolutionFromXML&#39;. Replace the first line in the try 
block:

            x = get_XML_Node(string(&quot;#&quot;)+id, &root);

with this line:

             x = get_XML_NameID(nm, string(&quot;#&quot;)+id, &root);

Save the file, and rebuild and install Cantera. Now your program should 
work.

By the way, if you use the &#39;ctnew&#39; utility to create a Makefile for 
your application, the include statements in your program do not work.  
I changed the statements

#include &quot;Cantera.h&quot;
#include &quot;IdealGasMix.h&quot;

to

#include &lt;cantera/Cantera.h&gt;
#include &lt;cantera/IdealGasMix.h&gt;

and it compiled and ran.


Dave




